Certainly! To write a command to a console window and hit the enter key programmatically in C#, you can use the `SetForegroundWindow`, `SendKeys`, and `FindWindow` functions from the `user32.dll` library. Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates how to achieve this:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;

class Program
{
    // Import user32.dll functions
    [DllImport("user32.dll")]
    private static extern bool SetForegroundWindow(IntPtr hWnd);

    [DllImport("user32.dll")]
    private static extern IntPtr FindWindow(string lpClassName, string lpWindowName);

    [DllImport("user32.dll")]
    private static extern IntPtr FindWindowEx(
        IntPtr hWndParent,
        IntPtr hWndChildAfter,
        string lpszClass,
        string lpszWindow);

    [DllImport("user32.dll", CharSet = CharSet.Auto)]
    private static extern int SendMessage(
        IntPtr hwnd,
        int wMsg,
        IntPtr wParam,
        IntPtr lParam);

    private const int WM_KEYDOWN = 0x100;
    private const int WM_KEYUP = 0x101;
    private const int VK_RETURN = 0x0D;

    static void Main()
    {
        string consoleWindowTitle = "YourConsoleWindowTitle";

        // Find the console window
        IntPtr hwndConsole = FindWindow(null, consoleWindowTitle);

        if (hwndConsole != IntPtr.Zero)
        {
            // Set the console window as the foreground window
            SetForegroundWindow(hwndConsole);

            // Simulate typing the command and sending the 'Enter' key
            SendKeysToConsole("YourCommand{ENTER}");
        }
        else
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Console window not found!");
        }

        Console.ReadLine();
    }

    static void SendKeysToConsole(string keys)
    {
        foreach (char key in keys)
        {
            SendMessage(
                FindWindowEx(IntPtr.Zero, IntPtr.Zero, "ConsoleWindowClass", null),
                WM_KEYDOWN,
                (IntPtr)key,
                IntPtr.Zero);

            SendMessage(
                FindWindowEx(IntPtr.Zero, IntPtr.Zero, "ConsoleWindowClass", null),
                WM_KEYUP,
                (IntPtr)key,
                IntPtr.Zero);
        }
    }
}
```

Make sure to replace `"YourConsoleWindowTitle"` with the actual title of the console window you want to interact with and `"YourCommand"` with the command you want to send. The `{ENTER}` placeholder is used to simulate pressing the enter key.

Note: This code assumes that you have the necessary permissions to send messages to another application's window.

